The graph of $g(x) = \ln x$ looks like this:

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{MER_MATH110_December_2012_Question_1b_ln.jpg}
\caption{MER MATH110 December 2012 Question 1b ln.jpg}
\end{figure}

Using function rules for the graph of $g(x) = \ln(1 - x)$

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  the negative in front of the \emph{x} means the graph has been
  reflected over the y-axis and
\item
  \emph{(1-x)} inside the function means that it is shifted right 1
\end{itemize}

giving:

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{MER_MATH110_December_2012_Question_1b_shifted_ln.jpg}
\caption{MER MATH110 December 2012 Question 1b shifted ln.jpg}
\end{figure}

If you've forgotten the rules used in the first solution (or never
learned them), you can also facts about the domain of $\ln(x)$ to
determine where the graph should go.

The domain of the function $f(x) = \ln (x)$ is $x > 0$ which can be seen
in the graph below.

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{MER_MATH110_December_2012_Question_1b_ln.jpg}
\caption{MER MATH110 December 2012 Question 1b ln.jpg}
\end{figure}

The graph of $g(x) = \ln(1-x)$ will have a similar shape, but has a
different domain. Let's test some values to see where the domain of this
function is.

\begin{longtable}[c]{@{}lll@{}}
x-value & & y-value\\

-2 & $\ln(1 - (-2)) = \ln(3)$ & $\ln(3)$\\
-1 & $\ln(1 - (-2)) = \ln(2)$ & $\ln(2)$\\
0 & $\ln(1 - 0) = \ln(1)$ & 0\\
1 & $\ln(1 - 1) = \ln(0)$ & undefined\\
2 & $\ln(1 - 2) = \ln(-1)$ & undefined\\
\end{longtable}

So clearly this function is defined on the domain $x < 1$,

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{MER_MATH110_December_2012_Question_1b_restricted_domain.jpg}
\caption{MER MATH110 December 2012 Question 1b restricted domain.jpg}
\end{figure}

suggesting the graph looks something like this:

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{MER_MATH110_December_2012_Question_1b_shifted_ln.jpg}
\caption{MER MATH110 December 2012 Question 1b shifted ln.jpg}
\end{figure}
